# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: common-rail
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:common-rail/aerosol] An **aerosol** is a suspension of fine solid particles or liquid droplets in air or another gas.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Aerosols can be generated from natural or human causes.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The scientific term *aerosol* refers to the mixture of particulates in gas, and not to the particulate matter alone.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The liquid or solid particles in an aerosol have diameters typically less than 1 μm.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Larger particles with a significant settling speed make the mixture a suspension, although the distinction is not clear.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Examples of natural aerosols are fog, mist, and dust from geological or biological sources.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Certain infections spread by means of small droplets in the breath, sometimes called bioaerosols.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Volcanic aerosol forms in the stratosphere after an eruption as droplets of sulfuric acid that can prevail for up to two years, and reflect sunlight, lowering temperature.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Desert dust, mineral particles blown to high altitudes, absorb heat and may be responsible for inhibiting storm cloud formation.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] In everyday language, *aerosol* often refers to a dispensing system that delivers a consumer product from a spray can.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Other examples of human caused aerosols include perfume from atomizers, medical treatments for respiratory illnesses, dust from material or industrial sources, smoke, irrigation mist, sprayed pesticides, particulate air pollutants, and mist from the discharge at hydroelectric dams.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Human-made sulfate aerosols, primarily from burning oil and coal, affect the behavior of clouds.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] When aerosols absorb pollutants, it facilitates the deposition of pollutants to the surface of the earth as well as to bodies of water.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This has the potential to be damaging to both the environment and human health.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Ship tracks are clouds that form around the exhaust released by ships into the still ocean air.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Water molecules collect around the tiny particles (aerosols) from exhaust to form a cloud seed.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] More and more water accumulates on the seed until a visible cloud is formed.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] In the case of ship tracks, the cloud seeds are stretched over a long narrow path where the wind has blown the ship's exhaust, so the resulting clouds resemble long strings over the ocean.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The warming caused by human-produced greenhouse gases has been somewhat offset by the cooling effect of human-produced aerosols.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] In 2020, regulations on fuel significantly cut sulfur dioxide emissions from international shipping by approximately 80%, leading to an unexpected global geoengineering termination shock.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Aerosol is defined as a suspension system of solid or liquid particles in a gas.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] An aerosol includes both the particles and the suspending gas, which is usually air.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Meteorologists and climatologists often refer to them as particle matter, while the classification in sizes ranges like PM2.5 or PM10, is useful in the field of atmospheric pollution as these size range play a role in ascertain the harmful effects in human health.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Donnan presumably first used the term *aerosol* during World War I to describe an aero-solution, clouds of microscopic particles in air.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This term developed analogously to the term hydrosol, a colloid system with water as the dispersed medium.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] *Primary aerosols* contain particles introduced directly into the gas; *secondary aerosols* form through gas-to-particle conversion.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Key aerosol groups include sulfates, organic carbon, black carbon, nitrates, mineral dust, and sea salt, they usually clump together to form a complex mixture.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Various types of aerosol, classified according to physical form and how they were generated, include dust, fume, mist, smoke and fog.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] There are several measures of aerosol concentration.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Environmental science and environmental health often use the *mass concentration* (*M*), defined as the mass of particulate matter per unit volume, in units such as μg/m3.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Also commonly used is the *number concentration* (*N*), the number of particles per unit volume, in units such as number per m3 or number per cm3.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Particle size has a major influence on particle properties, and the aerosol particle radius or diameter (*dp*) is a key property used to characterise aerosols.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] A *monodisperse* aerosol, producible in the laboratory, contains particles of uniform size.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Most aerosols, however, as *polydisperse* colloidal systems, exhibit a range of particle sizes.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Liquid droplets are almost always nearly spherical, but scientists use an *equivalent diameter* to characterize the properties of various shapes of solid particles, some very irregular.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The equivalent diameter is the diameter of a spherical particle with the same value of some physical property as the irregular particle.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The *equivalent volume diameter* (*de*) is defined as the diameter of a sphere of the same volume as that of the irregular particle.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Also commonly used is the aerodynamic diameter, *da*.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, that originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Although all hydrometeors, solid and liquid, can be described as aerosols, a distinction is commonly made between such dispersions (i.e. clouds and precipitation) containing relatively large water drops or ice crystals, and aerosol particles.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The presence of aerosols in the Earth's atmosphere can influence its climate, as well as human health.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Volcanic eruptions release large amounts of sulphuric acid, hydrogen sulfide and hydrochloric acid into the atmosphere.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] These gases represent aerosols and eventually return to earth as acid rain, having a number of adverse effects on the environment and human life.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Aerosols interact with the Earth's energy budget in two ways, directly and indirectly.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Aerosol particles with an effective diameter smaller than 10 μm can enter the bronchi, while the ones with an effective diameter smaller than 2.5 μm can enter as far as the gas exchange region in the lungs, which can be hazardous to human health.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] For a monodisperse aerosol, a single number—the particle diameter—suffices to describe the size of the particles.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] However, more complicated particle-size distributions describe the sizes of the particles in a polydisperse aerosol.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This distribution defines the relative amounts of particles, sorted according to size.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] One approach to defining the particle size distribution uses a list of the sizes of every particle in a sample.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] However, this approach proves tedious to ascertain in aerosols with millions of particles and awkward to use.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Another approach splits the size range into intervals and finds the number (or proportion) of particles in each interval.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The particle size distribution can be approximated.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The normal distribution usually does not suitably describe particle size distributions in aerosols because of the skewness associated with a long tail of larger particles.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Also for a quantity that varies over a large range, as many aerosol sizes do, the width of the distribution implies negative particles sizes, which is not physically realistic.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] However, the normal distribution can be suitable for some aerosols, such as test aerosols, certain pollen grains and spores.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The log-normal distribution has no negative values, can cover a wide range of values, and fits many observed size distributions reasonably well.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] For low values of the Reynolds number (<1), true for most aerosol motion, Stokes' law describes the force of resistance on a solid spherical particle in a fluid.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] However, Stokes' law is only valid when the velocity of the gas at the surface of the particle is zero.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] For small particles (< 1 μm) that characterize aerosols, however, this assumption fails.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] To account for this failure, one can introduce the Cunningham correction factor, always greater than 1.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This allows us to calculate the terminal velocity of a particle undergoing gravitational settling in still air.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] is the terminal settling velocity of the particle.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The terminal velocity can also be derived for other kinds of forces.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] If Stokes' law holds, then the resistance to motion is directly proportional to speed.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] To account for the effect of the shape of non-spherical particles, a correction factor known as the *dynamic shape factor* is applied to Stokes' law.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The aerodynamic diameter of an irregular particle is defined as the diameter of the spherical particle with a density of 1000 kg/m3 and the same settling velocity as the irregular particle.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] One can apply the aerodynamic diameter to particulate pollutants or to inhaled drugs to predict where in the respiratory tract such particles deposit.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Pharmaceutical companies typically use aerodynamic diameter, not geometric diameter, to characterize particles in inhalable drugs.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The previous discussion focused on single aerosol particles.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] In contrast, *aerosol dynamics* explains the evolution of complete aerosol populations.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The concentrations of particles will change over time as a result of many processes.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] External processes that move particles outside a volume of gas under study include diffusion, gravitational settling, and electric charges and other external forces that cause particle migration.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] A second set of processes internal to a given volume of gas include particle formation (nucleation), evaporation, chemical reaction, and coagulation.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] A differential equation called the *Aerosol General Dynamic Equation* (GDE) characterizes the evolution of the number density of particles in an aerosol due to these processes.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] As particles and droplets in an aerosol collide with one another, they may undergo coalescence or aggregation.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This process leads to a change in the aerosol particle-size distribution, with the mode increasing in diameter as total number of particles decreases.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] On occasion, particles may shatter apart into numerous smaller particles; however, this process usually occurs primarily in particles too large for consideration as aerosols.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] where $\lambda$ is the mean free path of the suspending gas and d is the diameter of the particle.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] For particles in the *free molecular regime*, *Kn* >> 1; particles small compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] In this regime, particles interact with the suspending gas through a series of "ballistic" collisions with gas molecules.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] As such, they behave similarly to gas molecules, tending to follow streamlines and diffusing rapidly through Brownian motion.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] where *a* is the particle radius, *P*∞ and *PA* are the pressures far from the droplet and at the surface of the droplet respectively, *kb* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *CA* is mean thermal velocity and *α* is mass accommodation coefficient.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The derivation of this equation assumes constant pressure and constant diffusion coefficient.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Particles are in the *continuum regime* when Kn << 1.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] In this regime, the particles are big compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas, meaning that the suspending gas acts as a continuous fluid flowing round the particle.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The *transition regime* contains all the particles in between the free molecular and continuum regimes or *Kn* ≈ 1.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The forces experienced by a particle are a complex combination of interactions with individual gas molecules and macroscopic interactions.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] where *I*cont is the mass flux in the continuum regime.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This formula is called the Fuchs-Sutugin interpolation formula.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] These equations do not take into account the heat release effect.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Aerosol partitioning theory governs condensation on and evaporation from an aerosol surface, respectively.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Condensation of mass causes the mode of the particle-size distributions of the aerosol to increase; conversely, evaporation causes the mode to decrease.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Nucleation is the process of forming aerosol mass from the condensation of a gaseous precursor, specifically a vapor.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Net condensation of the vapor requires supersaturation, a partial pressure greater than its vapor pressure.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Chemical reactions may increase the partial pressure of a gas or lower its vapor pressure.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The addition of additional vapor to the system may lower the equilibrium vapor pressure according to Raoult's law.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] There are two types of nucleation processes.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Gases preferentially condense onto surfaces of pre-existing aerosol particles, known as **heterogeneous nucleation**.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This process causes the diameter at the mode of particle-size distribution to increase with constant number concentration.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] With sufficiently high supersaturation and no suitable surfaces, particles may condense in the absence of a pre-existing surface, known as **homogeneous nucleation**.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This results in the addition of very small, rapidly growing particles to the particle-size distribution.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Water coats particles in aerosols, making them *activated*, usually in the context of forming a cloud droplet (such as natural cloud seeding by aerosols from trees in a forest).
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Following the Kelvin equation (based on the curvature of liquid droplets), smaller particles need a higher ambient relative humidity to maintain equilibrium than larger particles do.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] where $p_{s}$ is the saturation vapor pressure above a particle at equilibrium (around a curved liquid droplet), *p*0 is the saturation vapor pressure (flat surface of the same liquid) and *S* is the saturation ratio.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] where *rp* droplet radius, *σ* surface tension of droplet, *ρ* density of liquid, *M* molar mass, *T* temperature, and *R* molar gas constant.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Aerosols can either be measured in-situ or with remote sensing techniques either ground-based on airborne-based.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Particles can deposit in the nose, mouth, pharynx and larynx (the head airways region), deeper within the respiratory tract (from the trachea to the terminal bronchioles), or in the alveolar region.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The location of deposition of aerosol particles within the respiratory system strongly determines the health effects of exposure to such aerosols.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] This phenomenon led people to invent aerosol samplers that select a subset of the aerosol particles that reach certain parts of the respiratory system.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Examples of these subsets of the particle-size distribution of an aerosol, important in occupational health, include the inhalable, thoracic, and respirable fractions.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The fraction that can enter each part of the respiratory system depends on the deposition of particles in the upper parts of the airway.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The inhalable fraction of particles, defined as the proportion of particles originally in the air that can enter the nose or mouth, depends on external wind speed and direction and on the particle-size distribution by aerodynamic diameter.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The thoracic fraction is the proportion of the particles in ambient aerosol that can reach the thorax or chest region.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The respirable fraction is the proportion of particles in the air that can reach the alveolar region.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] To measure the respirable fraction of particles in air, a pre-collector is used with a sampling filter.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The pre-collector excludes particles as the airways remove particles from inhaled air.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The sampling filter collects the particles for measurement.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] It is common to use cyclonic separation for the pre-collector, but other techniques include impactors, horizontal elutriators, and large pore membrane filters.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] Two alternative size-selective criteria, often used in atmospheric monitoring, are PM10 and PM2.5.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] PM10 is defined by ISO as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 10 μm aerodynamic diameter* and PM2.5 as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 2.5 μm aerodynamic diameter*.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] PM10 corresponds to the "thoracic convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, Clause 6; PM2.5 corresponds to the "high-risk respirable convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, 7.1.
[src:common-rail/aerosol] The United States Environmental Protection Agency replaced the older standards for particulate matter based on Total Suspended Particulate with another standard based on PM10 in 1987 and then introduced standards for PM2.5 (also known as fine particulate matter) in 1997.
[src:common-rail/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:common-rail/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:common-rail/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:common-rail/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:common-rail/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:common-rail/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:common-rail/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:common-rail/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:common-rail/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:common-rail/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:common-rail/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:common-rail/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:common-rail/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:common-rail/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The **Alfa Romeo 156** (Type 932) is a compact executive car produced by the Italian automobile manufacturer Alfa Romeo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] It was introduced at the 1997 Frankfurt Motor Show as the replacement for the Alfa Romeo 155.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 received a positive reception and in the following year went on to win the 1998 European Car of the Year award.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 saloon was discontinued in Europe late in 2005, while the Q4 Crosswagon continued in production until the end of 2007.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Cars were assembled at the Fiat Group factory in Pomigliano d'Arco, Italy and at a General Motors facility in Rayong, Thailand.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Production in Thailand began in March 2002 and ran for only a couple of years.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The cars produced there were targeted for the Asia-Pacific markets.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 was available in saloon, *Sportwagon* (estate) and *Crosswagon* (crossover) bodystyles with seven engine configurations; it went through two facelifts, first in 2002 and then in 2003.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Sportwagon advertising campaign was made featuring actress Catherine Zeta-Jones.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] In 2005, the 159 became the replacement for the 156.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The range also included a straight-5 2.4-litre 10-valve 136 PS (100 kW) *JTD* common rail turbodiesel engine.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Until January 2002, the range-topping engine was the venerable 2.5-litre 24-valve *Busso* V6 - now with double overhead camshafts and four-valve heads - rated at 190 PS (140 kW).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Initially the 156 range was available with different options (packs) like a sport pack that included Blitz clothing, Momo leather interior and Recaro seats, it also included 16-inch (410 mm) wheels, lowered suspension and leather-trimmed steering wheel and gear knob.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Lusso pack added with Momo's mahogany steering wheel and gear knob and for Nordic countries, a special winter pack consisting of fog lights, headlight washers, and heated seats was available.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] A significant addition to the 156 range came in 2000 with the introduction of the **Sportwagon** station wagon or estate bodystyle, debuting at the Geneva Motor Show.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The new bodystyle was in development from 1998 by Stola under the project code '932 AF'.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] According to Stola's records the initial considered name was "Powerwagon".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] While not a core part of the company's range, estate versions of the Alfasud and 33 - the first to carry the name Sportwagon - were produced and a 75 Sportwagon was shown at Geneva, but became an early victim of the Fiat takeover.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Sportwagon was also available with Boge-Nivomat self-levelling hydropneumatic rear suspension.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Sportwagon was marketed as a lifestyle estate without large carrying capacity.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Sportwagon bodystyle filled a gap in the market that Alfa Romeo had distanced themselves from since the 33 SportWagon of the 1980s.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Designed by Alfa Centro Stile under the guidance of head designer Walter de'Silva the 156s shape was intended to be distinctly Alfa Romeo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Its styling included high, curved flanks, retro styled front door handles, recessed rear door handles, and a deep grille requiring an off-centre licence plate holder.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The design featured visually deemphasized rear door handles and accentuated front handles, giving the illusion of a coupé profile.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The design was influenced by the Alfa Romeo 1900, Giulietta and Giulia.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 achieved a drag coefficient (*C*d) of 0.31.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The original interior uses a scalloped upper dashboard and a simple centre console.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The main controls and displays are angled to the driver.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 Sportwagon features fold-down rear seats to increase the luggage area normally covered by a privacy screen.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] 2002 saw an update to both the interior and exterior of the 156.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] 2002 also saw the arrival of a facelifted interior with different matte-finish surfacing and chrome highlights.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] This new version featured the 147's dual-zone digital climate controller while the interior climate could also be controlled via an air quality sensor.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] A different choice of colours were available for the interior, with the option of a two-tone interior very much like that on offer from its European rivals.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] A wider range of options including xenon lighting, tele-informatics (CONNECT and CONNECT NAV) and a Bose stereo system were available, the stereo system could now also be operated via buttons on the steering wheel.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Also, the *Selespeed* gearbox control system was updated, buttons on the steering wheel were replaced by paddle shifters, as seen on the earlier Alfa Romeo 147.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] In the center console, the designers added a multifunctional display with trip computer, fault, and service monitor.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The upgrade also included electronic stability control VDC (Vehicle Dynamic Control) with an emergency brake assist device and slip control ASR (Anti Slip Regulation) came as standard.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Additionally, an MSR (Motor Schleppmoment Regelung) was added to the car, this device prevents wheel skidding by restoring torque to the engine for example when the gear is shifted down abruptly under conditions of low grip.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Passive safety was also made better, all versions got window airbags as standard.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 2.0 L *JTS* 165 PS (121 kW) engine with gasoline direct injection replaced the 2.0-litre Twin Spark engine, offering more low end torque and more power than the Twin Spark.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The only notable difference exterior-wise was body-coloured mirrors and bumper strips which were earlier black.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Late 2003 saw the launch of a facelifted 156, with new front and rear fascias designed by Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] A new top-of-the-line model was added to the line up called TI (Turismo Internazionale) designating a sporty kit, this version was equipped with modified suspension, bigger wheels (215/45 17") and leather-trimmed interior.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The GTA models never received the exterior update.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Diesel engines underwent a major overhaul which included a new four-valve per cylinder heads and a second stage common rail injection with 1400 bar maximum injection pressure with up to five injections per cycle for lower noise, consumption, and higher performance.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The **156 GTA** and **156 Sportwagon GTA** were launched at the Frankfurt Motor Show in September 2001.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The GTA was named after the Alfa Romeo GTA from the 1960s, the letters GTA meaning Gran Turismo Alleggerita (English: lightened Grand Tourer).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Developed alongside the 147 GTA, it was an exclusive high-performance model hand assembled on a dedicated production line separate to the standard 156 models.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Development of the GTA styling models and engineering design was entrusted in early 2000 to Stola with styling data provided by Centro Stile.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Stola completed six prototypes that were further mechanically assembled by Alfa Romeo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Two of those protypes were presented at the Frankfurt Motor Show.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] 2,973 berlinas and 1,678 Sportwagons were built until the GTA production stopped in October 2005, as the V6 engine as unable to meet emissions regulations and due to the 156 being replaced by the 159.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The GTA was sold in limited numbers, with right-hand drive vehicles holding a premium over left-hand drive vehicles due to their rarity.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The very first GTA was sold via online auction, from 13 to 23 September, the duration of the Frankfurt Motor Show.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Winning bid was €48,691.26, which was donated to "Telethon" charity fund.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 3.2-litre *Bussone* V6 engine (The big Busso, so-called after legendary Alfa Romeo engineer Giuseppe Busso).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] This engine is praised universally for its sound and revving capabilities.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] This was the largest iteration of the engine built by Alfa Romeo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The engine has a 93 mm (3.7 in) bore and a 78 mm (3.1 in) stroke, displacing at 3,179 cc (194.0 cu in).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Overall, the car weighed 55 kg (121 lb) more than the standard V6 156.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The GTA variants shared a common interior with post-facelift 156 variants.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The doors, boot lid and bonnet were also shared.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] All else was unique to the GTA, with the engine specifically made by Fiat and Maserati Research Centres.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The GTA did not receive the Giugiaro designed facelift introduced on the 156 in 2003, but continued with the acclaimed Walter de Silva design to the very end of production.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The steering was also made faster, only 1.7 turns from lock to lock compared to 2.1 in normal models.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The GTA had also larger brakes (Brembo), at front 305 millimetres (12.0 in) discs and rear 276 millimetres (10.9 in).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The front discs were later upgraded to 330 millimetres (13 in) to cope with the performance potential.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] In 2004 **Sportwagon Q4**, an all-wheel drive version of the Sportwagon was launched in some markets.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Q4 (short for Quadrifoglio 4) system used three differentials, the central one being of the Torsen C limited slip type; it added about 150 kg (331 lb) to the vehicle weight.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Graziano Trasmissioni, the Turin-based transmission specialist, developed this system.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] A raised ride height meant the Sportwagon Q4's was 1,458 mm (57.4 in) tall.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Other than the ride height, special 5-spoke 17-inch wheels and a "Q4" badge on the tail set the Sportwagon Q4 apart from the front-wheel drive 156 versions.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Sportwagon Q4 was only available on LHD markets, with no RHD models being built or sold.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The only available engine was the 1.9 M-Jet diesel with 150 PS (110 kW; 148 hp).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The **Crosswagon Q4** was launched in 2004 with a crossover look and enhanced off-road capabilities.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Crosswagon's ride height was raised further compared to the Sportwagon Q4, giving the car better approach and departure angles; at 1,497 mm (58.9 in) it was 6.5 cm (2.6 in) taller than a standard 156.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Tall-sidewall all-season tyres on 17 inch wheels were standard.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The only available engine was 1.9 M-Jet diesel rated at 150 PS (110 kW; 148 hp).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Crosswagon was made to look more like an all-terrain vehicle by unique front and rear bumpers and door sills with steel inserts.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] After the introduction of the 159 in 2005 the Crosswagon remained in production, and in 2007 it was the last 156 model to be discontinued.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The Alfa Romeo 156 GTAm was shown at the Bologna Motor Show in December 2002.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The car was built by Fiat Group's partner N.Technology.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The car had widened wheel arches, 19 inch tyres and was equipped with N.Technology limited slip differential.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] This car never reached production phase.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] At the 2004 Geneva Motor Show Italian-based tuning firm Autodelta unveiled a 156 Sportwagon prototype equipped with a 3,548 cc (3.5 L; 216.5 cu in) V6 engine that developed 300 PS (221 kW) at 6,800 rpm.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The car was fitted with Bilstein adjustable shock absorbers, Eibach springs and Brembo front brakes with a diameter of 330 millimetres (13 in).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Weight was reduced using a composite engine bonnet.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] London-based tuning firm Autodelta made two high performance versions based on the 156 GTA: in the GTA AM version, the Alfa Romeo V6 engine was bored to 3,750 cc (3.8 L; 228.8 cu in), making it capable of 328 PS (241 kW) at 7,300 rpm.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] With this, the car could attain a top speed of 282 km/h (175.2 mph) and accelerate to 100 km/h in 5.2 s.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The GTA AM Super was an upgrade of the first version, now fitted with a Rotrex supercharger and rated at 400 PS (294 kW).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 uses a platform derived from the Alfa Romeo 155, (together with Fiat Bravo/Brava/Marea), which in turn was derived from the Fiat Group's "Tipo" (Also known as C1) platform.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] However, it is sufficiently different from the original "Tipo" one to be seen as a new platform.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] This version of the C1 (Type 2) platform has significant modifications to its suspension, chassis, and rigidity, making it not a simple "clone" or "rebadge" of the Bravo/Brava.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] This structure means that the rear wheels have a tiny passive steering ability.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Weight saving materials (mainly aluminium) have been used in several parts both front and rear suspension.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] For the 156 GTA, weight saving materials were also used in many other parts like magnesium framed front seats and dashboard frame.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 GTA only shared common parts with other 156 variants with respect to the facelift interior, doors, bonnet and boot lid.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 2.4 JTD diesel was world's first common rail diesel engine in a passenger car.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Note (*): Crosswagon Q4 topspeed is 192 km/h (119 mph) and acceleration 0–100 km/h (62,5 mph) is 10.5 seconds, for Sportwagon Q4 numbers are 200 km/h (124 mph) and 10.2 seconds.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] In 1998, an international jury of 56 journalists (40 of whom voted for the 156) representing 21 countries awarded the Alfa 156 the European Car of the Year award; it was described as having a "very refined suspension layout so to offer an impeccable roadholding".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 2.5 V6 engine was awarded with the International Engine of the Year award in 2000.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 competed in various motor racing championships including the World Touring Car Championship, European Touring Car Championship and the British Touring Car Championship.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 touring car program was run by Fiat Group's partner N.Technology S.p.A., founded as Nordauto Squadra Corse, to compete in the Italian Touring Car Championship.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] In 1994, the name was changed to Nordauto Engineering, and to N.Technology in 2001.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] In 1998, the 156 Group N version was offered for sale to the public.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The 156 Group N had no carpets, seats or upholstery, but included additional track safety devices.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] Italian race car constructor Coloni made a one-off racing car prototype for FIA Group-E Formula Libre called the Coloni S1 Alfa Romeo 156, or 156 Maxiturismo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The car is a carbon fibre silhouette racing car on a tubular frame, powered by a 3.0-litre Alfa Romeo V6 engine rated between 380 and 500 hp (280 and 370 kW).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] The car has a 6-speed Hewland-Coloni sequential gearbox and weighs around 900 kilograms (2,000 lb).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-156] It is capable of attaining speeds of over 310 kilometres per hour (190 mph).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Founded on 24 June 1910 in Milan, Italy as **A.L.F.A.**—an acronym for *Anonima Lombarda Fabbrica Automobili*—the company was established by Cavaliere Ugo Stella to acquire the assets of the ailing Italian subsidiary of French carmaker Darracq, of which he had been an investor and manager.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Its first car was the 24 HP, designed by Giuseppe Merosi, which became commercially successful and participated in the 1911 Targa Florio endurance race.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In August 1915, ALFA was acquired by Neapolitan entrepreneur and engineer Nicola Romeo, who vastly expanded the company's portfolio to include heavy machinery and aircraft engines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1920, the company's name was changed to **Alfa Romeo**, with the Torpedo 20–30 HP being the first vehicle to bear the new brand.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Through the 1920s, Alfa Romeo produced several successful road and race cars, and was well represented in prominent European motorsport events, notably winning the inaugural AIACR World Manufacturers' Championship at the 1925 Grand Prix season.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Nevertheless, the company soon faced financial troubles, leading to Romeo's contentious departure in 1928 and Italian government ownership in 1933.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Under the control of the industrial organization *Institute for Industrial Reconstruction* (IRI), Alfa Romeo initially continued making its signature custom luxury vehicles, but following the financial hardship of World War II, shifted to mass-producing small vehicles.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1954, it launched the Giulietta series of family cars and developed the Alfa Romeo Twin Cam engine, which would remain in production until 1994.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo became known for producing mass-market vehicles that nonetheless blended the aesthetics and performance of sport and luxury marques.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Despite its strong brand image and relatively sizeable share of the high-performance auto market in Europe, by the 1970s, the company was operating at a loss, prompting IRI to sell it to Fiat Group in 1986.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo has since maintained its distinct identity and brand through several ownership changes, including Fiat's merger with the American Chrysler Group in 2014, forming Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), and FCA's subsequent merger in 2021 with the French PSA Group to form Stellantis.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo is heavily involved in various motorsports—including Grand Prix motor racing, Formula One, sportscar racing, touring car racing, and rallies—with achievements giving a sporty image to the marque.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Enzo Ferrari founded the Scuderia Ferrari racing team in 1929 as an Alfa Romeo racing team, before forming his namesake luxury sports car maker in 1939.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The company's name is a combination of the original name, "A.L.F.A." ("Anonima Lombarda Fabbrica Automobili" - “Lombardian Automobile Factory Corporation”), and the last name of entrepreneur Nicola Romeo, who took control of the company in 1915.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The first factory building of A.L.F.A. was in the first-place property of **Società Anonima Italiana Darracq** (SAID), founded in 1906 by the French automobile firm of Alexandre Darracq, with some Italian investors.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] One of them, Cavaliere Ugo Stella, an aristocrat from Milan, became chairman of the SAID in 1909.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In late 1909, the Italian Darracq cars were selling slowly and the company was wound up.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Ugo Stella, with the other Italian co-investors, founded a new company named **A.L.F.A.** (Anonima Lombarda Fabbrica Automobili), buying the assets of Italian Darracq that was up to dissolution.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The first car produced by the company was the 1910 24 HP, designed by Giuseppe Merosi, hired in 1909 for designing new cars more suited to the Italian market.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Merosi would go on to design a series of new A.L.F.A. cars, with more powerful engines such as the 40–60 HP.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] A.L.F.A. ventured into motor racing, with drivers Franchini and Ronzoni competing in the 1911 Targa Florio with two 24-hp models.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1914, an advanced Grand Prix car was designed and built, the GP1914, with a four-cylinder engine, double overhead camshafts, four valves per cylinder, and twin ignition.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] However, the onset of the First World War halted automobile production at A.L.F.A. for three years.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In August 1915, the company came under the direction of Neapolitan entrepreneur Nicola Romeo, who converted the factory to produce military hardware for the Italian and Allied war efforts.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Munitions, aircraft engines and other components, compressors, and generators based on the company's existing car engines were produced in a vastly enlarged factory during the war.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] After the war, Romeo invested his war profits in acquiring locomotive and railway carriage plants in Saronno (Costruzioni Meccaniche di Saronno), Rome (Officine Meccaniche di Roma), and Naples (Officine Ferroviarie Meridionali), which were added to his A.L.F.A. ownership.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Car production had not been considered at first, but resumed in 1919 since parts for the completion of 105 cars had remained at the A.L.F.A. factory since 1915.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1920, the name of the company was changed to Alfa Romeo with the Torpedo 20–30 HP the first car to be so badged.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Their first success came in 1920 when Giuseppe Campari won at Mugello and continued with second place in the Targa Florio driven by Enzo Ferrari.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Giuseppe Merosi continued as head designer, and the company continued to produce solid road cars as well as successful race cars (including the 40–60 HP and the RL Targa Florio).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1923, Vittorio Jano was lured from Fiat, partly due to the persuasion of a young Alfa racing driver named Enzo Ferrari, to replace Merosi as chief designer at Alfa Romeo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The first Alfa Romeo under Jano was the P2 Grand Prix car, which won Alfa Romeo the inaugural world championship for Grand Prix cars in 1925.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Jano's designs proved both reliable and powerful.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Enzo Ferrari proved a better team manager than a driver, and when the factory team was privatised, it became Scuderia Ferrari.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] When Ferrari left Alfa Romeo, he went on to build his own cars.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Tazio Nuvolari often drove for Alfa, winning many races before the Second World War.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1928, Nicola Romeo left, and in 1933 Alfa Romeo was rescued by the government, which then had effective control.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo became an instrument of Mussolini's Italy, a national emblem.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] During this period, it built bespoke vehicles for the wealthy, with bodies normally by Carrozzeria Touring or Pininfarina.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] This era peaked with the Alfa Romeo 2900B Type 35 racers.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Alfa factory (converted during wartime to the production of Macchi C.202 Folgore engines: the Daimler-Benz 600 series built under license) was bombed during the Second World War and struggled to return to profitability after the war.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Smaller, mass-produced vehicles began to be produced beginning with the 1954 model year, with the introduction of the Giulietta series of *berline* (saloons/sedans), coupes and open two-seaters.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] All three varieties shared what would become the Alfa Romeo overhead Twin Cam four-cylinder engine, initially displacing 1300 cc.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] This engine would eventually be enlarged to 2000 cc and would remain in production until 1995.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Once motorsports resumed after the Second World War, Alfa Romeo proved to be the car to beat in Grand Prix events.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The introduction of the new formula (Formula One) for single seat racing cars provided an ideal setting for Alfa Romeo's Tipo 158 Alfetta, adapted from a pre-war voiturette, and Giuseppe Farina won the first Formula One World Championship in 1950 in the 158.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Juan Manuel Fangio secured Alfa's second consecutive championship in 1951.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1952, Alfa Romeo experimented with its first front-wheel-drive compact car, "Project 13–61".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] It had the same transverse-mounted, forward-motor layout as the modern front-wheel-drive automobile.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo made a second attempt in the late 1950s based on Project 13–61.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] It was to be called Tipo 103 and resembled the smaller version of its popular Alfa Romeo Giulia.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] However, due to the financial difficulties in post-war Italy, the Tipo 103 never saw production.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Had Alfa Romeo produced it, it would have preceded the Mini as the first "modern" front-wheel-drive compact car.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the mid-1950s, Alfa Romeo entered into an agreement with Brazil's Matarazzo Group to create a company called Fabral (*Fábrica Brasileira de Automóveis Alfa*, "the Brazilian Alfa automobile factory") to build the Alfa Romeo 2000 there.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] After having received government approval, Matarazzo pulled out under pressure from Brazil's President Juscelino Kubitschek with the state-owned FNM company instead commenced building the car as the "FNM 2000" there in 1960.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] During the 1960s, Alfa Romeo concentrated on motorsports using production-based cars, including the GTA (standing for Gran Turismo Allegerita), an aluminium-bodied version of the Bertone-designed coupe with a powerful twin-plug engine.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Among other victories, the GTA won the inaugural Sports Car Club of America's Trans-Am championship in 1966.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the 1970s, Alfa Romeo concentrated on prototype sports car racing with the Tipo 33, with early victories in 1971.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Eventually the Tipo 33TT12 gained the World Championship for Makes for Alfa Romeo in 1975 and the Tipo 33SC12 won the World Championship for Sports Cars in 1977.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] As Alfa Romeo was a state-controlled company, they were often subject to political pressure.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] To help industrialize Italy's underdeveloped south, Alfa Romeo's new compact car was to be built at a new factory at Pomigliano d'Arco in Campania.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Even the car's name, *Alfa Sud* (Alfa South), reflected where it was built.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] 18 January 1968, saw a new company named "Industria Napoletana Costruzioni Autoveicoli Alfa Romeo-Alfasud S.p.A." being formed, 90% of which belonged to Alfa Romeo and 10% to Government controlled holding company Finmeccanica.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] This plant was built in the wake of France's 1968 protests and Italy's Hot Autumn and was never "properly started." The employees had mainly construction backgrounds and were not trained for factory work, while industrial relations were troublesome throughout.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Absenteeism rates in the Pomigliano factory ran at 16.5 percent through the 1970s, reaching as high as 28 percent.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] By the 1970s, Alfa Romeo was again in financial trouble, with the company running at about sixty percent of capacity in 1980.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Since Alfa Romeo was controlled by the Italian government owned Istituto per la Ricostruzione Industriale (IRI), a deal was made where about a quarter of worker's salaries were paid through state unemployment agencies to allow Alfa's plants to idle for two weeks every two months.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] An aging product lineup and very low productivity combined with near-permanent industrial unrest and Italy's high inflation rates kept Alfa Romeo firmly in the red.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Other creative measures were attempted to shore up Alfa, including an ultimately unsuccessful joint venture with Nissan endorsed by Alfa's then-president, Ettore Massacesi, and Prime Minister Francesco Cossiga.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] By 1986, IRI was suffering heavy losses—with Alfa Romeo having not been profitable for the last 13 years—and IRI president Romano Prodi put Alfa Romeo up for sale.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Finmeccanica, the mechanical holdings arm of IRI and its predecessors owned Alfa Romeo since 1932.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Prodi first approached fellow Italian manufacturer Fiat, which offered to start a joint venture with Alfa.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Fiat withdrew its plan for a joint venture with Alfa Romeo when Ford put in an offer to acquire part of Alfa Romeo and restructure the company, while increasing its stake over time.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] However, Fiat chose to put in a bid to acquire the entirety of Alfa Romeo and offer job guarantees to Italian workers, an offer that Ford was unwilling to match.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] It also did not hurt any of the parties involved that an acquisition by Fiat would keep Alfa Romeo in Italian hands.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1986, the deal was concluded with Alfa Romeo merged with traditional rival Lancia into Fiat's Alfa Lancia Industriale S.p.A.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Already in 1981, Alfa Romeo's then-President Ettore Massacesi had stated that Alfa would never use Fiat engines—the engines being, to a large extent, Alfa Romeo's identity—but would be happy to cooperate fully with everything else.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 2005, Maserati was bought back from Ferrari and was now under Fiat's full control.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Fiat Group then created a sports and luxury division from Maserati and Alfa Romeo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] There is a planned strategic relationship between these two; engines, platforms and possibly dealers are shared.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the beginning of 2007, Fiat Auto S.p.A. was reorganized and four new automobile companies were created; Fiat Automobiles S.p.A., Alfa Romeo Automobiles S.p.A., Lancia Automobiles S.p.A. and Fiat Light Commercial Vehicles S.p.A.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] These companies were fully owned by Fiat Group Automobiles S.p.A.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] On 24 June 2010, Alfa Romeo celebrated 100 years from its foundation.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo has been suffering from falling sales.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 2010, it sold a total of about 112,000 units, which was significantly lower than Fiat CEO Marchionne's global sales target of 300,000.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The company set about to achieve a sales target of 170,000 units in 2011, including 100,000 Giulietta and 60,000 MiTo models, but it actually sold 130,000 units that year.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Its medium-term target was 500,000 units by 2014 including 85,000 from the North American market.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 2017 Alfa Romeo increased production by 62 percent, building a total of 150,722 vehicles at the company's three factories.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] On 16 January 2021, the operations of Fiat Chrysler Automobiles and Groupe PSA were merged to form Stellantis and the company was renamed Stellantis Italy.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In spite of falling sales, Alfa Romeo CEO Jean-Philippe Imparato announced in 2021 that a new model would be launched every year between 2022 and 2026, starting with the much-delayed Tonale, with full electrification of new models from 2027.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo was imported to the United States by Max Hoffman from the mid-1950s.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Giulietta Spider was developed on the request of Max Hoffman, who proposed an open top version of the Giulietta.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1961 Alfa Romeo started exporting cars to the United States through its own dealer network.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1995, Alfa Romeo ceased exporting cars to the United States, the last model sold in that market being the 164 sedan.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] On 5 May 2006, Alfa Romeo made its return to the US Market as announced by Fiat CEO Sergio Marchionne after a series of rumours.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] North American sales resumed in October 2008, with the launch of the limited production 8C Competizione coupe with Alfa Romeo models being imported by Fiat's US subsidiary Chrysler.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Also in 2008, Alfa Romeo and Chrysler were reported to be in discussions over the possibility of producing Alfa Romeo cars in some Chrysler manufacturing plants that had shut down due to the company group's restructure and cost cutting.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Instead, as reported by *The Wall Street Journal* in November 2009, Chrysler discontinued several Dodge and Jeep models while phasing in Alfa Romeo ones and the new Fiat 500.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The next significant milestones in Alfa Romeo's North American return occurred in 2014, with the launch of the more affordable two-seater 4C coupe.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] That year, Fiat Group Automobiles S.p.A. confirmed that its original agreement with Mazda Motor Corporation, for the speculated manufacturing of a new Alfa Romeo Spider based on the Mazda MX-5 had been terminated mutually in December 2014.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The proposed model for this joint venture became the Fiat 124 Spider convertible launched in 2015.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 2015, Alfa Romeo's return to this market was further bolstered by the automaker's display of the new Giulia at the Los Angeles Auto Show.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In February 2017, Chrysler featured its Alfa Romeo brand exclusively in three ads during Super Bowl LI.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo's US importer, FCA US LLC, currently imports the Giulia, Stelvio, Tonale and 33 Stradale.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo has introduced many technological innovations over the years, and the company has often been among the first users of new technologies.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Its trademark double overhead cam engine was used for the first time in the 1914 Grand Prix car, the first road car with such an engine, the 6C 1500 Sport, appeared in 1928.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo tested one of the first electronic fuel injection systems (Caproni-Fuscaldo) in the Alfa Romeo 6C 2500 with "Ala spessa" body in 1940 Mille Miglia.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The engine had six electrically operated injectors, fed by a semi-high pressure circulating fuel pump system.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] 1969 models for the North American market had SPICA (Società Pompe Iniezione Cassani & Affini, a subsidiary of Alfa Romeo) mechanical fuel injection.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] According to Alfa Romeo, the engine's power output and performance were unchanged from the carburetted version.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The SPICA system continued until the 1982 model year with the introduction of 2.0 liter Bosch electronic fuel injection.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Mechanical variable valve timing was introduced in the Alfa Romeo Spider, sold in the U.S. in 1980.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] All Alfa Romeo Spider models from 1983 onward used electronic VVT.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The 105 series Giulia was quite an advanced car, using technologies such as all-wheel disc brakes, and a plastic radiator header tank.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] It had also the lowest drag coefficient (Cd) in its class The same trend continued with the Alfetta 2000 and GTV, which had quirks such as 50:50 weight distribution, standard fit alloy wheels and transaxle.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Newer innovations include complete CAD design process used in designing the Alfa Romeo 164 and an automated/paddle-shift transmission called *Selespeed* used in the 156; the 156 was also the world's first passenger car to use Common rail diesel engine.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Multiair -an electro-hydraulic variable valve actuation technology used in MiTo was introduced in 2009.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 2016, the Alfa Romeo Giulia came with electrical brakes.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Many famous automotive design houses in Italy have accepted commissions to produce concepts and production vehicle shapes for Alfa Romeo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Construction techniques used by Alfa Romeo has been imitated by other carmakers, and in this way, the Alfa Romeo body designs have often been very influential.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The *Berlina Aerodinamica Tecnica* prototype cars were designed by Bertone as an exercise in determining whether streamlining and wind-tunnel driven designs would result in high performance on a standard chassis and whether the resulting vehicles would be palatable to the public.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa 1900 Sprint were the basis of the B.A.T.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Tipo 33 racing car, with its high-revving 2000 cc V8 engine became the basis for a number of different concept cars during the 1960s and 1970s, two of which ultimately resulted in production vehicles.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Most made their appearances at the Auto Salon Genève.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In general, concept cars for Alfa Romeo have generally become production vehicles, after some modification to make them suitable for manufacture, and to provide driver and passenger safety.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Zagato SZ, GTV, and Spider, Brera, and 159 are all good examples of Alfa Romeo's stylistic commitment in this direction.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The logo was originally designed in 1910 by a young Italian draughtsman from the A.L.F.A. technical office, Romano Cattaneo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In June 1910, the Società Anonima Darracq became Anonima Lombarda Fabbrica Automobili, and was readying its first model, the 24 HP.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The board asked chief engineer Giuseppe Merosi to devise a badge for the radiator shell of the new car; Merosi turned to his collaborators.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] One of them, Cattaneo, was inspired by the coat of arms he had seen on the gates of Castello Sforzesco to include the *biscione* in the logo.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Merosi liked the idea, and together with Cattaneo came up with a sketch, then approved by managing director Ugo Stella; Cattaneo was entrusted with doing the final design.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In honour of the King of Italy, the two words were separated by two figure-eight knots—named Savoy knots in Italian, and symbols of the then-reigning House of Savoy.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Originally solid brass, the lettering was changed to white enamel in 1913.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1918, after the company had been bought by Nicola Romeo, the wording "ALFA" was replaced with "ALFA-ROMEO".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1925, to commemorate the victory of the Alfa Romeo P2 in the inaugural World Manufacturers' Championship of 1925, a silver metal laurel wreath was added around the badge, used (in varying form) until 1982.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The addition of the wreath had enlarged the badge to 75 mm (3.0 in) diameter; in 1930 it was reduced back to 60 mm (2.4 in).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1946, after the abolition of the monarchy and proclamation of the Italian Republic, the figure-eight knots of the Savoy were replaced with two curvy lines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Concurrently the badge was completely redesigned, and further reduced in size to 54 mm (2.1 in), a diameter unchanged ever since.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Made of stamped steel, the new badge bore the traditional elements—the scripts, the cross, a newly stylized *biscione* and a thin laurel wreath—embossed in antique silver, over a uniform Alfa Red background, which had replaced the blue, white and light blue fields.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] This red-and-metal badge was used until 1950, when the company switched back to a traditionally enamelled and coloured one; in 1960 the badge was changed from brass to plastic, without substantial differences in design.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] At the beginning of the 1970s the all-new Alfa Romeo Pomigliano d'Arco plant (near Naples) was completed.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] When in 1972 the Alfasud produced there became the first Alfa Romeo passenger car manufactured outside Milan, the word "Milano", the curved lines and the hyphen between "Alfa" and "Romeo" were eliminated from the badge on all Alfa Romeos.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] At the same time it was redesigned, most notably acquiring a modernised *biscione* and typeface.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] After a mild restyling in 1982, which deleted the wreath and changed lettering and all chrome details to gold, this iteration of the badge remained in use until 2015.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] On 24 June 2015, 105th anniversary of the company, a new logo was unveiled at a press event at the Alfa Romeo Museum; together with the Alfa Romeo Giulia as part of the brand's relaunch plan.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The redesign was carried out by Robilant Associati, who had previously reworked several other Fiat Group logos—including Fiat Automobiles' and Lancia's.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The logo colors have been reduced from four to three: the green of the *biscione*, the red of the cross, and the dark blue of the surrounding ring.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Other changes are a new serif type face, and the absence of the split white and light blue fields, replaced by a single silver textured background.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Since 1923, the *quadrifoglio* logo (also called the 'cloverleaf') has been the symbol of Alfa Romeo racing cars and since WWII, it has also been used to designate the higher trim models of the range.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The *quadrifoglio* is usually placed on the side panels of the car, above or behind the front wheels—on the front wings in the case of modern vehicles.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The logo consists of a green (or in some cases golden) cloverleaf with four leaves, contained with a white triangle.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The *quadrifoglio* has been used on Alfa Romeo cars since the death of Ugo Sivocci in 1923.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] As a friend of Enzo Ferrari, Sivocci was hired by Alfa Romeo in 1920 to drive in the four-man works team—Alfa Corse—with Antonio Ascari, Giuseppe Campari, and Enzo Ferrari.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Sivocci was thought to have enormous experience, but often hampered by bad luck and considered the eternal second-placer.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] To banish his bad luck, when the Targa Florio came around, the driver painted a white square with a green four-leaf clover (the *quadrifoglio*) in the centre of the grille of his car.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Sivocci had immediate success, crossing the finish line first.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The *quadrifoglio* subsequently became the symbol of the racing Alfa Romeos with the victory at the Targa Florio.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Almost as if to prove the magic effects of this symbol, Sivocci was killed while testing Merosi's new P1 at Monza, a few months after winning the Targa Florio.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Salerno driver's P1, which went off the track on a bend, did not have the *quadrifoglio*.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Since this period in 1923, the bodies of Alfa Romeo racing cars have been adorned with the *quadrifoglio* as a lucky charm.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The white square was replaced with a triangle in memory of Ugo Sivocci.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The first road car to bear the *quadrifoglio* was the 1963 Alfa Romeo Giulia TI Super, a variant of the Giulia saloon car devised for competition but put regularly on sale; it had green four-leaf clovers on its front wings, without the triangle.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the 1970s "Quadrifoglio Verde" or "Green Cloverleaf" became the trim level for each model's sportiest variant, equipped with the most powerful engine.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Alfasud, Sprint, 33, 75, 164 and 145 all had Quadrifoglio Verde versions.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Also in the 1970s and through the 1980s golden four-leaf clover badges were used to denote the most luxurious and well-equipped variants of Alfa Romeo cars, named "Quadrifoglio Oro" or "Gold Cloverleaf".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Alfasud, Alfetta, Alfa 6, 90 and 33 had Quadrifoglio Oro versions.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In recent times the *quadrifoglio* was revived on the 2007 Alfa Romeo 8C Competizione and Spider sports cars.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] With the Alfa Romeo MiTo and Giulietta, the Quadrifoglio Verde was reinstated as the sportiest trim level in the range, and green four-leaf clovers on the front wings are once again the hallmark of high-performance Alfa Romeos.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo's 2016 sport sedan, the all-new Giulia, was launched first in Quadrifoglio trim before the release of the base models.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo has been involved with motor racing since 1911, when it entered two 24 HP models in Targa Florio competition.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo won the first World Manufacturers' Championship in 1925 and the first AIACR European Championship in 1931 and it scored wins at many races and motoring events such as Targa Florio, Mille Miglia and Le Mans.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Great success continued with Formula One, when Alfa Romeo won the first World Formula One Championship in 1950 and won the second Formula One Championship in 1951.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The company also won international championships in Prototypes, Touring and Fast Touring categories in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Private drivers also entered some rally competitions, with good results.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo has competed both as a constructor and an engine supplier, via works entries Alfa Corse, Autodelta and private entries.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo's factory racing team was outsourced to Enzo Ferrari's Scuderia Ferrari between 1933 and 1938.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Drivers included Tazio Nuvolari, who won the 1935 German Grand Prix at the Nürburgring.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo have been in a technical partnership with the Sauber F1 Team since 2018.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In February 2019, Sauber announced that it would compete as Alfa Romeo Racing although the ownership, racing licence and management structure would remain unchanged.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Alfa Romeo ended their partnership with Sauber and left Formula One after the 2023 season.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the 1960s, the main Alfa Romeo factory was moved from inside Milan to a very large and nearby area extending over the municipalities of Arese, Lainate and Garbagnate Milanese.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] However, since then the factory was moved to Arese, as the offices and the main entrance of the area were located there.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of European automobile manufacturers established facilities in South Africa to assemble right hand drive vehicles.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Fiat and other Italian manufacturers established factories along with these other manufacturers, Alfa-Romeos were assembled in Brits, outside Pretoria in the Transvaal Province of South Africa.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] With the imposition of sanctions by Western powers in the 1970s and 1980s, South Africa became self-sufficient, and in car production came to rely more and more on the products from local factories.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] This led to a set of circumstances where between 1972 and 1989, South Africa had the greatest number of Alfa Romeos on the road outside of Italy.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Alfa Romeos Brits plant was used from March 1983 until late 1985 to build Daihatsu Charades for local consumption, but also for export to Italy in order to skirt Italian limits on Japanese imports.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] For the last year the company was operating, the Daihatsu represented close to half of Alfa Romeo S.A.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In late 1985, with the impending Fiat takeover and an international boycott of the South African Apartheid government, Alfa Romeo withdrew from the market and closed the plant.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] During the 1990s, Alfa Romeo moved car production to other districts in Italy.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Pomigliano d’Arco plant produced the 155, followed by the 145 and the 146, while the Arese plant manufactured the SZ and RZ sports cars, the 164, the new Spider and the GTV.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The 156 was launched in 1997 and in 1998 was voted "Car of the Year".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The same year a new flagship, the 166 (assembled in Rivalta, near Turin) was launched.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] At the beginning of the third millennium, the 147 was released, which won the title of "European Car of the Year 2001".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 2003 the Arese factory was closed while only having some offices and the Alfa Romeo Historical Museum.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the 1960s, Alfa Romeo became famous for models specifically designed for Italian police and Carabinieri (Italian national gendarmerie); among them the "Giulia Super" and the 2600 Sprint GT.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The colours of the Alfa Romeos used by the police (Polizia) were/are green/blue with white stripes and writing, known as "Pantera" (Panthers).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The Carabinieri Alfa Romeros are dark blue with white roofs and red stripes, known as the "Gazzella" (Gazelles), a nickname meant to denote the speed and agility of these "Pattuglie" (patrol cars).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] However, the term "Pantera" came to be used interchangeably to refer to both agencies' vehicles, and helped create a public perception of the cars as no-nonsense, determined and respected.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Since then, Alfa Romeos remain the chosen vehicle of the Carabinieri, Polizia Autostradale (highway police), Guardia di Finanza (fiscal law enforcement) and the conventional police service (Polizia).
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The following Alfa Romeo cars have/can be found in service with the Italian police and/or government.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Since the 1960s, the Italian Prime Minister has used Alfa Romeos (and lately the new Maserati Quattroporte) as preferred government limousines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The 164 and 166 have found been particularly utilized in the last two decades.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In 1930, Alfa Romeo presented a light truck in addition to heavy LCVs based on Büssing constructions.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In the Second World War Alfa Romeo also built trucks for the Italian army ("35 tons anywhere") and later also for the German Wehrmacht.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] After the war, commercial motor vehicle production was resumed.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] In co-operation with FIAT and Saviem starting from the 1960s different light truck models were developed.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The production of heavy LCVs in Italy was terminated in 1967.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Heavy trucks continued to be built for a few years in Brazil by Alfa Romeo subsidiary Fábrica Nacional de Motores under the name FNM.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The last Alfa Romeo vans were the Alfa Romeo AR6 and AR8, rebadged versions of Iveco Daily and Fiat Ducato.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] The company also produced trolleybuses for many systems in Italy, Latin America, Sweden, Greece, Germany, Turkey and South Africa.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p01] Later, Alfa Romeo concentrated only on passenger car manufacturing.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Although Alfa Romeo is best known as automobile manufacturer it has also produced commercial vehicles of various size, railway locomotives, tractors, buses, trams, compressors, generators, an electric cooker, marine and aircraft engines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] An Alfa engine was first used on an aircraft in 1910 on the Santoni-Franchini biplane.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In 1932 Alfa Romeo built its first real aircraft engine, the D2 (240 bhp), fitted to Caproni 101 D2.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In the 1930s when Alfa Romeo engines were used for aircraft on a larger scale; the Savoia Marchetti SM.74, Savoia-Marchetti SM.75, Savoia-Marchetti SM.79, Savoia Marchetti SM.81 and Cant Z506B Airone all used Alfa Romeo manufactured engines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In 1931, a competition was arranged where Tazio Nuvolari drove his Alfa Romeo 8C 3000 Monza against a Caproni Ca.100 airplane.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Alfa Romeo built various aircraft engines during the Second World War; the best known was the RA.1000 RC 41-I Monsone, a licensed version of the Daimler-Benz DB 601.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] This engine made it possible to build efficient fighter aircraft like the Macchi C.202 Folgore for the Italian army.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] After the Second World War Alfa Romeo produced engines for Fiat, Aerfer and Ambrosini.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In the 1960s Alfa Romeo mainly focused upgrading and maintaining Curtiss-Wright, Pratt & Whitney, Rolls-Royce and General Electric aircraft engines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Alfa Romeo also built Italy's first turbine engine, installed to the Beechcraft King Air.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Alfa Romeo's Avio division was sold to Aeritalia in 1988, from 1996 it was part of Fiat Avio.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Alfa Avio was also part of developing team to the new T700-T6E1 engine to the NHI NH90 helicopter.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Alfa Romeo also produced marine engines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] The first marine engine was produced in 1929.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Later, for three consecutive years: 1937-1938-1939 with remarkable affirmations, Alfa Romeo demonstrated its constructive efficiency by contributing to the development of marine engines.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] During the years Alfa Romeo has been marketed with different slogans like: "The family car that wins races" used in the 1950s in Alfa Romeo 1900 marketing campaign, "racing since 1911" used on most 1960s Alfa advertisements.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In the 1970s the Alfa Romeo 1750 GTV was marketed as "if this kind of handling is good enough for our racing cars, it's good enough for you." The Giulia Sprint GTA was marketed as "The car you drive to work is a champion".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] More recent slogans used are "Mediocrity is a sin", "Driven by Passion", "Cuore Sportivo", "Beauty is not enough" and present day "Without heart we would be mere machines".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Also other more recent ones are: "It's not a car, it's an Alfa Romeo.", one of them after a couple argue in Italian.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] As part of its marketing policy, Alfa Romeo sponsors a number of sporting events, such as the Mille Miglia rally.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] It has sponsored the SBK Superbike World Championship and Ducati Corse since 2007, and the Goodwood Festival of Speed for many years, and was one of the featured brands in 2010 when Alfa Romeo celebrated its 100th anniversary.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] The Alfa Romeo Giulietta has been used since Monza 2010 race as the safety car in Superbike World Championship events.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Alfa Romeo has been also shirt sponsor of Eintracht Frankfurt football club in period between 2013 and 2016.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In 2002, *Alfa Romeo I*, the first Alfa Romeo super maxi yacht was launched.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] It finished first in at least 74 races including the 2002 Sydney—Hobart Race.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] *Alfa Romeo II*, commissioned in 2005, measures 30 metres (98 ft) LOA.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] It set a new elapsed-time record for monohulls in the 2009 Transpac race, of 5 days, 14 hours, 36 minutes, 20 seconds.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] It finished first in at least 140 races.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In mid-2008 *Alfa Romeo III* was launched for competitive fleet racing under the IRC rule.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] *Alfa Romeo III* measures 21.4 metres (70 ft) LOA and features interior design styled after the Alfa Romeo 8C Competizione.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] The BBC motoring show *Top Gear* repeatedly argued the significance of owning an Alfa Romeo car as a car enthusiast, stating that "You can't be a true petrolhead if you have never owned/or wanted to own an Alfa Romeo".
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Presenters Jeremy Clarkson, Richard Hammond and James May continuously praised Alfas for their beauty and driving characteristics even though Italian cars had a long-term bad reputation for unreliability.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] They argued that the owner build a personal relationship with the car despite all of its mechanical faults.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Both Clarkson and May have previously owned Alfas (a GTV6 for Clarkson and an Alfa 164 for May) and both have stated that they regretted selling their Alfas the most.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] As part of its U.S. relaunch, Alfa Romeo ran three commercials during Super Bowl LI; the brand was the sole marque advertised by FCA during the game, after exclusively focusing on its Jeep brand at Super Bowl 50.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] In February 2013, Alfa Romeo sponsored University of St Andrews FS fashion show which saw luxury fashion designer Luke Archer and milliner George Jenkins win with their Alfa Romeo inspired garments.
[src:common-rail/alfa-romeo-p02] Alfa Romeo announced Zhou Guanyu as China's first Formula One racing driver for the 2022 season, hailed by both the team and the sport as a historic breakthrough in a key growth market.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:common-rail/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Common rail injection is widely used in diesel engines.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] It is also the basis of gasoline direct injection systems used on petrol engines.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] In 1916 Vickers pioneered the use of mechanical common rail systems in G-class submarine engines.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] For every 90° of rotation, four plunger pumps allowed a constant injection pressure of 3,000 pounds per square inch (210 bar; 21 MPa), with fuel delivery to individual cylinders being shut off by valves in the injector lines.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] From 1921 to 1980 Doxford Engines used a common rail system in their opposed-piston marine engines, where a multicylinder reciprocating fuel pump generated a pressure around 600 bars (60 MPa; 8,700 psi), with fuel stored in accumulator bottles.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Pressure control was achieved by an adjustable pump discharge stroke and a "spill valve".
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Camshaft-operated mechanical timing valves were used to supply the spring-loaded Brice/CAV/Lucas injectors, which injected through the side of the cylinder into the chamber formed between the pistons.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Early engines had a pair of timing cams, one for ahead running and one for astern.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Later engines had two injectors per cylinder, and the final series of constant-pressure turbocharged engines was fitted with four.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] This system was used for the injection of both diesel and heavy fuel oil (600cSt heated to a temperature near 130 °C).
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Common rail engines have been used in marine and locomotive applications for some time.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The Cooper-Bessemer GN-8 (*circa* 1942) is an example of a hydraulically operated common rail diesel engine, also known as a modified common rail.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The common rail system prototype for automotive engines was developed in the late 1960s by Robert Huber of Switzerland, and the technology was further developed by Dr.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Marco Ganser at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Zurich, later of Ganser-Hydromag AG (est.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The first common-rail-Diesel-engine used in a road vehicle was the MN 106-engine by East German *VEB IFA Motorenwerke Nordhausen*.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] It was built into a single IFA W50 in 1985.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Due to a lack of funding, the development was cancelled and mass production was never achieved.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The first successful mass production vehicle with common rail, was sold in Japan in 1995.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Shohei Itoh and Masahiko Miyaki of the Denso Corporation developed the ECD-U2 common rail system, mounted on the Hino Ranger truck.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Denso claims the first commercial high-pressure common rail system in 1995.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Modern common rail systems are governed by an engine control unit, which controls injectors electrically rather than mechanically.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Prototyped in the 1990s by Magneti Marelli, Centro Ricerche Fiat in Bari, and Elasis, with further development by physicist Mario Ricco Fiat Group.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Unfortunately Fiat were in a poor financial state at this time, so the design was acquired by Robert Bosch GmbH for refinement and mass production.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The first passenger car to use this system was the 1997 Alfa Romeo 156 with a 2.4-L JTD engine, and later that same year, Mercedes-Benz introduced it in their W202 model.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] In 2001, common rail injection made its way into pickup trucks with the introduction of the 6.6 liter Duramax LB7 V8 used in the Chevrolet Silverado HD and GMC Sierra HD.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] In 2003 Dodge and Cummins launched common rail engines, and Ford followed in 2008 with the 6.4L Powerstroke.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Today almost all non-commercial diesel vehicles use common rail systems.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The common rail system is suitable for all types of road cars with diesel engines, ranging from city cars (such as the Fiat Panda) to executive cars (such as the Audi A8).
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The main suppliers of modern common rail systems are Bosch, Delphi Technologies, Denso, and Siemens VDO (now owned by Continental AG).
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Solenoid or piezoelectric valves make possible fine electronic control over the fuel-injection time and quantity, and the higher pressure that the common rail technology makes available provides better fuel atomisation.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Some advanced common rail fuel systems perform as many as five injections per stroke.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Common rail engines require a very short to no heating-up time, depending on the ambient temperature, and produce lower engine noise and emissions than older systems.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Diesel engines have historically used various forms of fuel injection.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Two common types include the unit-injection system and the distributor/inline-pump systems.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] In common rail systems, a high-pressure pump stores a reservoir of fuel at high pressure—up to and above 2,000 bars (200 MPa; 29,000 psi).
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The term "common rail" refers to the fact that all of the fuel injectors are supplied by a common fuel rail which is nothing more than a pressure accumulator where the fuel is stored at high pressure.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] This accumulator supplies multiple fuel injectors with high-pressure fuel.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] This simplifies the purpose of the high-pressure pump in that it only needs to maintain a target pressure (either mechanically or electronically controlled).
[src:common-rail/common-rail] The fuel injectors are typically controlled by the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:common-rail/common-rail] When the fuel injectors are electrically activated, a hydraulic valve (consisting of a nozzle and plunger) is mechanically or hydraulically opened and fuel is sprayed into the cylinders at the desired pressure.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Since the fuel pressure energy is stored remotely and the injectors are electrically actuated, the injection pressure at the start and end of injection is very near the pressure in the accumulator (rail), thus producing a square injection rate.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] If the accumulator, pump, and plumbing are sized properly, the injection pressure and rate will be the same for each of the multiple injection events.
[src:common-rail/common-rail] Third-generation common rail diesels now feature piezoelectric injectors for increased precision, with fuel pressures up to 2,500 bar (250 MPa; 36,000 psi).
